00:30:46.959 --> 00:30:51.199
Um, they don't have one, I think for Presto, which is where we have a lot of

00:30:51.199 --> 00:30:53.839
our layers kind of thrown out there from GCP.

00:30:54.400 --> 00:30:58.760
Um, so we, we have our own Presto, uh, connector that we use.

00:30:58.800 --> 00:31:02.040
I think there's the R Presto, uh, shiny power R package that

00:31:02.040 --> 00:31:03.520
you can use for connecting.

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:05.599
Um, but most of it's ODBC.

00:31:05.680 --> 00:31:09.000
We used to use JDBC, but we recently converted over.

00:31:09.479 --> 00:31:14.000
Um, and then I'll use like the database, like pool package to make sure that

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:17.880
connection stay on and revolving, uh, through big query, cause there is time

00:31:17.880 --> 00:31:21.239
out stuff, um, but yeah, I'll just connect through big query in that.

00:31:21.560 --> 00:31:26.280
I'll use DB plier, uh, either inside of the backend of shiny or for development

00:31:26.280 --> 00:31:30.520
of a SQL query, um, just to get a flow down and then me and my coworker

00:31:30.520 --> 00:31:33.760
usually work together if we need to use like Python's API to optimize it.

00:31:38.760 --> 00:31:39.239
Great.

00:31:39.479 --> 00:31:41.760
Um, I was just curious.

00:31:41.760 --> 00:31:47.359
So I know this is a tool that you provide to the merchants as well.

00:31:48.319 --> 00:31:52.640
Is this something that's like greatly improved their experience of working

00:31:52.959 --> 00:31:57.439
with Walmart, or I'm just trying to like put myself in the shoes

00:31:57.439 --> 00:31:59.000
of who's using the shiny app.

00:32:00.040 --> 00:32:04.760
Honestly, I think, I think at this point, it doesn't help them process wise,

00:32:05.520 --> 00:32:08.599
but that's, that's the whole point about connecting to these systems is to

00:32:08.599 --> 00:32:11.959
actually improve their processes with the data now, now that we actually

00:32:11.959 --> 00:32:15.599
know what they need and what, what insights they're going for and where

00:32:15.599 --> 00:32:20.199
else we can build, um, right now it's, it's honestly probably more work.

00:32:20.680 --> 00:32:24.479
Because they, they come to our app, they find insights and then they've got to

00:32:24.479 --> 00:32:26.599
actually execute and do something to it.

00:32:27.040 --> 00:32:30.839
Um, and in the e-commerce space, that's typically always at all, unless

00:32:30.880 --> 00:32:33.880
we're putting aside of something specific in our fulfillment center.

00:32:34.560 --> 00:32:38.800
Um, so it's, it's probably harder actually for them right now because

00:32:38.800 --> 00:32:41.800
they, they need to drill in to understand what their gap is.

00:32:42.119 --> 00:32:46.119
Um, there's predictions to their category, so it could be incorrect.

00:32:46.119 --> 00:32:47.359
So they're giving us feedback.

00:32:47.920 --> 00:32:53.160
Um, we have items mapped to it that are anywhere from 90 to a hundred percent,

00:32:53.359 --> 00:32:55.839
uh, similar, but that doesn't mean it's always right.

00:32:55.839 --> 00:32:58.040
It could be a short item description or something.

00:32:58.359 --> 00:33:00.479
And so we could be giving them a little bit of false information

00:33:00.479 --> 00:33:01.520
they have to sift through.

00:33:02.160 --> 00:33:07.239
Um, so yeah, I mean, it's, it's four to five, maybe six more steps than they're

00:33:07.239 --> 00:33:11.640
actually used to for the e-commerce space, but it's data they've never had

00:33:11.640 --> 00:33:16.599
before ever, and so it kind of outweighs it currently, but that's why we really

00:33:16.599 --> 00:33:20.439
need to push to getting this, this data inside of our item catalog so that when

00:33:20.439 --> 00:33:24.599
they come in shiny, give it, we can recommend, Hey, give us two things and

00:33:24.599 --> 00:33:28.560
we can set up the top item in your market with the supplier and that's it.

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:34.239
Instead of, Oh, here you found your item, go to this tool, set it up in the item

00:33:34.239 --> 00:33:38.479
process, go to this tool, add the supplier to our area, go to this

00:33:38.479 --> 00:33:40.359
tool, order some inventory for it.

00:33:40.839 --> 00:33:43.079
Now it's, it's becoming a little bit mundane.

00:33:43.319 --> 00:33:43.680
So.

00:33:46.479 --> 00:33:46.959
Thank you.

00:33:48.160 --> 00:33:51.880
I know we have people on the data science hangout from so many different

00:33:51.880 --> 00:33:56.599
like sizes of companies and different industries, and I was just curious,

00:33:56.839 --> 00:34:02.079
like, what's the biggest challenge that you've faced working at a company

00:34:02.079 --> 00:34:05.839
as large as Walmart and, and how do you overcome that?

00:34:06.760 --> 00:34:08.080
Uh, there's a lot.

00:34:08.320 --> 00:34:15.600
Um, so the size of the scale of our organization, just in merchandising

00:34:15.600 --> 00:34:20.560
means that you can't even send a total merchandising, uh, communication email.

00:34:21.320 --> 00:34:23.120
So you need to get the word out.

00:34:23.120 --> 00:34:24.040
It's not through that.

00:34:24.080 --> 00:34:25.120
What else are you going to use?

00:34:25.600 --> 00:34:28.439
Um, so it's, it comes down to a lot of word of mouth.

00:34:28.679 --> 00:34:31.959
It comes down to a lot of trust coming from the merchants.

00:34:32.399 --> 00:34:36.679
Um, even if you send out a mass communication email, you could be in

00:34:36.679 --> 00:34:40.239
the wrong quarter of planning for them to even look at your e-commerce space.

00:34:40.479 --> 00:34:41.919
So they don't care at that point.

00:34:41.919 --> 00:34:43.000
And then they forget about it.

00:34:43.120 --> 00:34:44.959
And then you need to send something else out again.

00:34:45.520 --> 00:34:49.760
Um, so a lot of it does come down to like, we'll do departmental strategy.

00:34:49.760 --> 00:34:52.639
So we'll go, Hey, we've got 55 departments.

00:34:53.080 --> 00:34:56.120
Uh, it's a lot of meetings, but if we can group some of them

00:34:56.120 --> 00:34:57.639
together, we can make a joint.

00:34:58.040 --> 00:35:01.679
And then we'll do maybe an hour, hour and a half demo of how you'd

00:35:01.679 --> 00:35:05.879
actually use the tool, what's coming up next and then the feedback session.

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:07.760
Uh, just some type of deep dive with them.

00:35:08.159 --> 00:35:11.120
Um, and then every quarter, like I said, there, there's the

00:35:11.159 --> 00:35:14.280
monthly, um, demo from the merchant side.

00:35:14.719 --> 00:35:17.679
Uh, that's the, that's the larger format one where they, where all

00:35:17.679 --> 00:35:19.159
departments are invited to come.

00:35:19.199 --> 00:35:20.280
They're not forced to come.

00:35:20.959 --> 00:35:23.679
Uh, but yeah, it's just calendar management.

00:35:24.120 --> 00:35:29.159
Um, being able to say no to certain tasks because you're going to have 300 people.

00:35:29.520 --> 00:35:30.520
Ask you about something.

00:35:30.520 --> 00:35:35.560
Cause you're a SME, um, and then communications and communications

00:35:35.560 --> 00:35:37.719
is almost always the hardest part.

00:35:38.360 --> 00:35:42.719
Um, especially if somebody gets ahold of your data asset and starts

00:35:42.719 --> 00:35:45.800
making, uh, somewhat the same tool as you.

00:35:46.320 --> 00:35:49.919
So then you have to fight for merchants using one tool or the other.

00:35:50.159 --> 00:35:50.479
So.

00:35:53.719 --> 00:35:54.199
Thank you.

00:35:54.199 --> 00:35:55.239
That's really helpful.

00:35:56.239 --> 00:35:59.840
Um, a followup question that came through about that is how do

00:35:59.840 --> 00:36:01.719
you decide what to say no to?

00:36:04.159 --> 00:36:05.760
Uh, business prioritization.

00:36:06.080 --> 00:36:10.000
Uh, so since I work on the business side, I don't really operate like tech.

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:15.840
It's not, um, like we kind of prioritize our own impact based on.

00:36:16.840 --> 00:36:18.520
Current versus long-term strategy.

00:36:18.800 --> 00:36:24.239
Like if we, if we just decided that we were going to move inventory

00:36:24.239 --> 00:36:28.120
from all of our fulfillment centers to the store, for some reason, then we

00:36:28.120 --> 00:36:30.120
would need to focus on that first.

00:36:30.439 --> 00:36:31.760
The business impact is there.

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:35.959
If we feel like we don't have the bandwidth right now, we have to turn it down and try

00:36:35.959 --> 00:36:37.280
to see if somebody else can support it.

00:36:37.600 --> 00:36:41.120
Um, otherwise, if we think that it trumped something that we're currently doing,

00:36:41.479 --> 00:36:45.840
we'll put one or two people on it, kick it out real fast, as fast as possible, and

00:36:45.840 --> 00:36:47.639
then go back to focusing on something else.

00:36:48.159 --> 00:36:52.239
But it always just comes down to like what we think is the most important

00:36:52.239 --> 00:36:54.320
at that time, which is a very generic answer.

00:36:54.879 --> 00:36:59.479
Um, you've got like, um, I don't know.

00:36:59.479 --> 00:37:01.159
It's not even based on dollar impact.

00:37:01.159 --> 00:37:03.879
It's maybe you have a data asset that you think is going to be more

00:37:03.879 --> 00:37:04.919
valuable in the longterm.

00:37:04.919 --> 00:37:09.280
You've got to work on it now, uh, because in next month, if you don't have it by

00:37:09.280 --> 00:37:13.479
next month, it's going to be a year before the merchants even come back to it again.

00:37:13.959 --> 00:37:17.040
So it's, it really does come down to like timeline planning.

00:37:17.199 --> 00:37:20.000
Um, especially at the store side.

