00:45:42.239 --> 00:45:45.439
shiny app while dealing with this huge amount of data?

00:45:46.479 --> 00:45:50.959
Uh, so once again, I'm lucky, uh, because of RStudio Connect.

00:45:51.040 --> 00:45:55.120
So we have a massive server behind it with a high

00:45:55.120 --> 00:45:57.000
availability and auto scaling.

00:45:57.639 --> 00:46:01.800
So that, that typically takes care of concurrency for the most part.

00:46:02.159 --> 00:46:06.679
Um, database pool also keeps connections alive for everybody to have

00:46:06.679 --> 00:46:09.520
pretty seamless experience of connections coming on and off, which

00:46:09.520 --> 00:46:11.679
doesn't overload our GCP project.

00:46:12.199 --> 00:46:17.800
Um, our queries, we, we, since we stage a lot of our data upfront that we do

00:46:17.800 --> 00:46:22.600
need, um, we make sure it's super targeted, everything's a star schema.

00:46:22.600 --> 00:46:27.399
If we can make it otherwise it's filtered specific to a merchant's hierarchy.

00:46:27.399 --> 00:46:28.800
So queries are really quick.

00:46:29.360 --> 00:46:32.760
Uh, I think the longest query that we actually have running in a production

00:46:32.760 --> 00:46:35.280
app today takes eight to nine seconds.

00:46:35.879 --> 00:46:39.360
Um, and so we, we don't deal with query concurrency too terribly.

00:46:39.800 --> 00:46:42.959
Um, most of the time, whenever people are making that nine second query, it's

00:46:42.959 --> 00:46:45.679
going to pull them back hundreds of thousands of items.

00:46:46.080 --> 00:46:49.199
Um, so they're going to be looking at that view for a long time.

00:46:49.239 --> 00:46:51.120
They're not going to be going to another thing.

00:46:51.840 --> 00:46:53.560
Um, I think it depends on your use case.

00:46:53.760 --> 00:46:58.760
So, uh, one issue we've seen is if you need to make, um, like

00:46:58.760 --> 00:47:01.159
large input sheet submissions.

00:47:01.520 --> 00:47:04.959
So what we like to do is, um, there's our hands on table package.

00:47:05.479 --> 00:47:10.080
If we require like 20 inputs or something for, for whatever reason, it's really

00:47:10.080 --> 00:47:11.639
easy to just record them there.

00:47:12.040 --> 00:47:16.479
Uh, but if you got 3000 merchants doing a different, different type of query, where

00:47:16.479 --> 00:47:20.639
it's actually submitting back to the database rather than pulling, uh, that's

00:47:20.639 --> 00:47:22.439
a different, that's, it's totally different.

00:47:22.439 --> 00:47:23.679
You have to handle it differently.

00:47:24.199 --> 00:47:27.120
Um, and so there, there has been some challenges with that.

00:47:27.120 --> 00:47:30.000
I'm still working around what the best practices for that.

00:47:30.320 --> 00:47:34.959
I use BQ upload, a BQ upload from the bigger query package for a

00:47:34.959 --> 00:47:37.080
really fast upload into our table.

00:47:37.560 --> 00:47:41.840
Um, and then we just try to make sure we partition and cluster anything possible,

00:47:42.040 --> 00:47:44.280
uh, just to make all of our tables run really fast.

00:47:44.360 --> 00:47:47.600
So, um, it's, it's a lot of thought.

00:47:47.879 --> 00:47:52.320
It's a lot of design and upfront, like, Hey, what can we do to reduce this

00:47:52.320 --> 00:47:55.479
data scale because it's never going to fit in the app if we don't.

00:47:55.959 --> 00:47:59.320
Uh, but eventually we get a small enough that our stuff's targeted.

